The Brand

Pokmon, (an abbreviation for Pocket Monsters in Japan) is a Japanese media franchise managed by The Pokmon Company, a company founded by Nintendo, Game Freak, and Creatures. The franchise was created by Satoshi Tajiri in 1995, and is centered on fictional creatures called "Pokmon". In Pokmon, humans, known as Pokmon Trainers, catch and train Pokmon to battle other Pokmon for sport. All media works within the franchise are set in the Pokmon universe. The English slogan for the franchise is "Gotta Catch Em All!". There are currently 900 Pokmon species.

In[3]:
corr = df.corr(method='pearson').abs()

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20,12))
ax = sns.heatmap(corr, annot=True, cmap='Blues', vmin=0, vmax=+1)

ax.axhline(18,0,18/34, ls='--', linewidth=3, color="red")
ax.axvline(18-0.05,16/34,34/34, ls='--', linewidth=3, color="red")
ax.axhline(0+0.05,0,18/34, ls='--', linewidth=3, color="red")
ax.axvline(0.05,16/34,34/34, ls='--', linewidth=3, color="red")

ax.axhline(18,18/34,34/34, ls='--', linewidth=3, color="green")
ax.axvline(18+0.05,0,16/34, ls='--', linewidth=3, color="green")
ax.axhline(34-0.07,18/34,34/34, ls='--', linewidth=3, color="green")
ax.axvline(34-0.07,0,16/34, ls='--', linewidth=3, color="green")

plt.title('Pearson Correlation')
plt.show()

Comments

  • We can see some correlations inside of attack types (red) and other general stats (green)
  • We can also see that general stats don't seem to affect the efficiency of attacks against specific types (not framed in green or red)

In[4]:
preprocessor = make_pipeline(MinMaxScaler())
numerics = ['int16', 'int32', 'int64', 'float16', 'float32', 'float64']
numeric_df = df.select_dtypes(include=numerics)
numeric_df = numeric_df.fillna(numeric_df.mean())
PCAPipeline = make_pipeline(preprocessor, PCA(n_components=3,random_state=0))

In[12]:
strength_df = pd.DataFrame()
strength_features = ['against_bug','against_dark','against_dragon','against_electric','against_fairy',
                     'against_fight','against_fire','against_flying','against_ghost','against_grass',
                     'against_ground','against_ice','against_normal','against_poison','against_psychic',
                     'against_rock','against_steel','against_water']
classic_features = ['attack','defense','hp','sp_attack','sp_defense','speed','type1','type2']
strength_df["against_overall"] = df[strength_features].sum(axis=1)
strength_df = pd.concat([df['name'],strength_df,df[classic_features]],axis=1)
strength_df.head()

Conclusion on types strength

By looking closely at the scatterplot above, you can tell that a little number of pokemons look way stronger than the others.

For instance : Schuckle is the most isolated pokemon. He is really week in attack but super strong in defense (can tank a lot) and is globally strong against other types

We also have Legendary pokemons who are a bit isolated, with really great stats (careful not strong against all types !) :

Mewtwo
Groudon
Kyogre
Latios

We can also notice that we have a group of 4 Rock pokemons and 3 Steel pokemons with high stats

Bastiodon
Carbink
Probopass
Regirock

Aggron
Steelix
Registeel

In opposite, we can find very week pokemons (mainly Normal types) such as :

Azurill
Igglybuff
Jigglypuff

On the topline, we have bug and rock pokemons which are really strong against all other types. A little preference for some rock pokemons who have better attack and defense stats (see paragraph above)

And at the bottomline, we have Steel pokemon who are considered the weakest against all other types

Conclusion

Play Rock and Bugs (and use Legendaries carefully)
